{"_id":"014f60e0-f2d4-11eb-9692-f99e8ed2f799","postId":"2013_02_async-oop-5-events-d852aaf4-5a90-3727-b614-43875912fa95","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2013/02/async-oop-5-events.html","replyTo":"d3d5ea70-f2bb-11eb-a6ad-f724f0d21894","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"Yes, that would also work, as long as you replace `List<T>` with a threadsafe collection or use a separate collection per invocation. The consuming event handler itself wouldn't be able to be `async` with that approach, but it could call an `async` method and \"save\" it. Logically, this is similar to the deferral approach, but using task instances instead of `IDisposable` and `await`.","date":"2021-08-01T14:23:14.442Z"}